snippet.textDisplay:
Okey so hi, prepare yourself for a lesson in Norwegian!
We have the same alphabet as you guys, we just have 3 more letters. "Æ, Ø & Å".
To pronunciate the letter "Ø" , you would have to make the same sound as you make right after you've pronunciated the first letter in "Murder". So I guess it can be compared to the "ur" sound, but without the "r" and still not the single "u" sound.


But also, you can just split up the word and go into google translate to learn it!
SØRFUGLØYA
Sør Fugl Øya
South Bird Island


Just learn one word at a time, and then put them all together!

snippet.textDisplay:
So I’m just gonna throw out here a theory that I found online (would love to link it but I can’t find it)
But the reason why Elsa froze had so much more significance than we looked at. The song said “but not too deep or you’ll be drowned”
At first ahtohallan was a river so the drowning part would make sense, but over time ahtohallan froze so it became a glacier, but we all know that.
Let’s go back to the pabbie’s words where he said something like “we thought that Elsa’s powers were too powerful, but now we hope it is enough” This is important as it works into this theory.
Elsa didn’t freeze because it was just too cold, she froze because her powers were not strong enough to protect her from the opposing powers from ahtohallan. The dark secrets of arendelle and the past were far stronger and evil than Elsa’s powers. Thus she was overwhelmed and froze (instead of drowning).
This movie has some scientific elements, but a lot of it is more magic, so looking at the completely logical side won’t really suffice.

snippet.textDisplay:
Hi, I am from Norway, butI do not want to make a video say Sørfulgøya.
In the Norwegian alphabet there is a similarly to the English alphabet, except from that we have 3 more letters.
Those 3 letters are 'Æ' (æ), 'Ø' (ø), and 'Å' (å) comes after 'Z' (z) in the said order (æ,ø,å). All three of them are vowels.

Pronunciation:
Æ: The æ-sound is similar to the 'a' in the english words "bad" and "sad".

Ø: The ø-sound is similar to the 'u' in "burn" and "sun".

Å: The å-sound is similar to the 'o' in "born" and "horns". 

Practicing:
Try practicing the sounds by saying the words with a long vowel. Example: Saying "bad" with a long 'a'; "baaad" - to practice the æ-sound.

And after you have been practicing the sounds, you can try pronouncing some Norwegian words with 'æ', 'ø', and 'å':

Bær (= Berries). This word is pronunced with pressure on 'æ' [Bææær]. Try saying "b,b,b", "æ,æ,æ" and "r,r,r" to practice.

Båt (= Boat). This word is pronounced with pressure on 'å' [Båååt]. Try saying "b,b,b", "å,å,å" and "t,t,t" to practice.

Bøker (= Books). This word is pronounced with pressure on 'ø' and 'e' [Bøøøkeeer]. Try saying each of the letters repeatedly to practice.

Some "funfacts"
"Bø!" is the Norwegian version of "Boo!" (when trying scare people). It can be said with both a short and long 'ø'.
"Bæ" is the Norwegian spelling and pronounciation of a sheep's bleating (English version: "Baah"). It can be said with both a short and long 'ø' (but mostly long)
Good luck!

snippet.textDisplay: OK... something to understand about weather... You use the justification that a 1 day ride doesn't change the weather much... I live in CA... and I live in what we call the lower desert.  Our winter temps range from 32 to 90, our summer temps from 80 to 115.  I can travel just 15 miles and be in mountains with winter temps from -20 to 40 and summer temps from 50 to 90.  I can travel in a different direction for 40 miles and be in a different valley area with coastal breezes that has both summer and winter temps ranging from 32-90, coastal areas tend to have more consistent weather.  Basically... you are absolutely wrong that because two places are "close" their weather will be close as well.  All temps Fahrenheit.

snippet.textDisplay:
I still take the stance that Elsa freezing has nothing to do with temperature, but rather with the time reversal.
She is using her ice powers to hack into the coded memory in her own DNA.
1) The first time we see her recreate past events in the Enchanted Forest she uses the DNA in the water in the surrounding area aka the sweat that fell in those past moments.
2)The second time she struggles, but eventually gets the image of their parents on the boat, likely due to ocean water being highly condensed with the DNA of other creatures.
3)When she created the memories of the past film they are ALL from her perspective and thus her DNA.
4)When she sees the events of her parents this will also be from her DNA, but deeper within and is also when she starts SLOWLY freezing.
5)When she reaches the memories of her Grandfather she has hacked into her own DNA further and the freezing starts to accelerate exponentially.
